  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen firsthand in my interactions with people in Bari's tech community. Growing up with a parent who has a PhD and another who doesn't, I've always been aware of how education and background can shape expectations. When I work retail, I often hear people say things like, 'You seem smart for someone who's not in STEM,' or 'Why are you even here if you're not a coder?' These comments, though unintentional, trigger a stress response that can make someone feel like they're failing before they've even started. Stereotype threat happens when someone's identity—like being a woman in engineering or a person from a non-STEM background—makes them worry about confirming negative stereotypes. In my experience, this stress can lead to poorer performance, especially in high-pressure environments. I think we absolutely should address it. For me, it's about creating spaces where people feel safe to try without fear of judgment. In Bari, where I live, we have small tech meetups and coding workshops, but they're often dominated by people who already feel confident in STEM. I'd love to see more inclusive events that welcome beginners, especially those who might feel out of place. It's not just about fixing the problem—it's about building a culture where everyone feels they belong. As someone curious but not an expert in this field, I believe the key is to normalize conversations about it and make sure people know it's okay to make mistakes. After all, if we don't talk about it, we'll keep letting people feel like they don't belong.",
